commentBody:
@Chris 

😂  That sounds about right.

Utah is a spooky state.

@Steve L 

"No, the Tuesday through Saturday puzzles post at 10:00 pm ET." 

The *other* puzzles -- other than the crossword. I was speaking of Connections and Strands; also Letter Boxed. My error that I spoke out of line with "all," since I don't touch the Bee and didn't know it drops at a different time. 

@Barry had already covered the crossword.

@Ken W. 

As long as an UPTURN is a business reversal, the clue is good. It doesn’t have to be the same thing. 

Similarly, if EAT IT means taking an L in one of its senses (and it does), that clue is also good. Clues and answers don’t have to be synonymous.

@Sean 

Congrats!!

That's awesome!!

@Mike 

A bit of word saucer-y.
You bowled me over.

@Mike 
I'm surprised there's not a cascade of replies today. Maybe peoples' imaginations dried up.

I guess we'll wipe the slate clean and start over tomorrow.

@jma 

I long ago lost all hope of ever keeping pace with the punsters here.

(And, no, there is no hidden pun in my post.  There never will be.)

@Mtmetz 

He's a big part of what makes this a special forum.

Not perfect, but special.

@Isabeau 

Thanks! Standardized tests were not really a thing here when I was in school several decades ago so your explanation provided me with a much better understanding of the issue than you probably imagine 🙂

These days the tests at the end of primary school and high school are probably somewhat akin to your standardized tests.

@Andrzej 

As I solved, I thought, Andrzej is going to question TAUGHT TO THE TEST.

I also wondered if you'd ever heard the rather idiomatic ME THREE.

@Linda Jo 

I've heard that, yes, and I can appreciate the casual cleverness of the wordplay there. It's not an expression I would probably ever use myself but I know what it means 👍🏾

@CCNY

I understand your frustration. On the other hand, the completely not-standardized system I experienced in school wasn't good, either. The evaluation criteria were never clear, and the highest graded student from one school could actually be worse than an average student from another one. There probably is no ideal solution to fairly test the whole population of students.

@Linda Jo 

The Connections Archive go back to game #370 on 6/15/2024.  The earliest Connections Companion article I could find was for game #376.  

So with Strands at game #358 perhaps something is in the works?

@G 

Almost none of my machines are eligible for Win11 and I have a client in the same boat.  This October will be like a mini Y2K :)

I've been noodling around with Linux Mint and a shell to emulate Windows.  Just in the early stages.

@John Carson 

Thanks for the info about the constructor. I really liked the words selected today! Made me think a bit, and some are fun to visualize and/or say. 

On my phone, the constructor's name is always covered by a banner promoting other games. I'm trying to get in the habit of scrolling to uncover it before starting the game!

@Kristopher 
When I was teaching (uk) standardised tests were introduced for primary age children and schools put into league tables of results that were published in the newspapers. 
TEACHING TO THE TEST has negative connotations because of some schools only teaching exactly what was to be tested, rather than a wider and more varied curriculum.

@CCNY 

Where I am right now, the only slush is in a glass of piña colada!  But then I thought, I didn’t think there was any precipitation in the forecast back home this week. 

Then I remembered, you don’t live in NYC.

@Cathy 

Yes, I had to look that up.

How soon will we see borahae in the puzzle?

@Cathy 
Cute. I found an entire on-line dictionary of these terms. Agree with Linda Jo, these are great late-week xword entries. Quit a few are very vowel-friendly…

<a href="https://tinyurl.com/42umd274" target="_blank">https://tinyurl.com/42umd274</a>

@Cathy 
I was surprised to hear that BTS overthrew the Assad regime in Syria. That's some powerful pop music!

Oh, that was HTS? (In the voice of Emily Litella) Never mind.

@kim mills 
Did you just ignore 54A?
Most themed puzzles (except rebuses) can be solved without understanding the theme, so no... the themes aren't necessary. They are just the cherry on top that makes it more enjoyable (or nuts, or chocolate, whatever your preference)  🙂

@Linda Jo 

A Lucy Dacus callout, nice! 

I listen to an actual radio station during the day (WFUV), and this latest release of hers is in regular rotation. I have really enjoyed her work, solo and in the "supergroup" Boy Genius.  :)

@Bill 

And streaming right now on WXPN is World Cafe with Lucy Dacus and Boy Genius.

xpn.org

@G 
Yes, I've probably heard a lot of their music, without the artists' name registering.

And you or somebody here has recommended WFUV before. They're playing some Roberta Flack now.

@Linda Jo 

Ha, it probably was me! 

Thanks for cluing me into WXPN. I hadn't thought about that station in a long time! (Various family members went to college in Philly.)

@Janine 
About half my completion time on any given morning is spent looking out the window, or trying not to nod off.

Needless to say, I stopped caring about my time "scores" a while ago.

@Cassie 
You were so close. SLMA was a government *sponsored* enterprise, meaning it was chartered by the government with the implication (but not guarantee) that taxpayer funds would be used if it went belly-up. Their HQ building is just up the road from me.

I honestly don't know how public/private student lending is these days, with all the "vote for me and I'll forgive your loans" nonsense of the last four years. I went to college on the GI Bill.

@Bill 
I think it was your recommendation a few weeks ago that alerted me to The Prydain Chronicles. I guess it wasn’t so much a hit over here as I hadn’t come across it. Found a used copy online and have just started reading; Taran is trapped in the land of the Fair Folk but I suspect not for long?
A great recommendation, I’m really enjoying it. The parallels with LOTR/The Hobbit are clear, but so well written I don’t resent it. Love the Welsh connection.

@sotto voce 
Just heard the news on the radio while stuck in traffic (a rare occurrence here).
Killing Me Softly will always be one of my favourite songs, with her soft beautiful voice.

@CaptainQuahog 

I'll miss your input including but not limited to all things marine related.

 I'm guilty of being negative some days lately.  It's hard not to be in these trying times.

@CaptainQuahog 

Understandable, but it will be our loss. 

Also, I left you a comment after your most recent comment to me on yesterday's puzzle, which I hope you'll read if you see this.

@Francis 

P. P. S.  I've come up with a phrase describing the almost irresistible urge to write how about how terrified I am:

Projective comment.

